<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12213f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12213f">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12213f"> 213(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> hero = living god</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">On a expliqu&eacute; la notion de h&eacute;ros, dans la cas des h&eacute;ros celtiques en particulier, par celle de roi-dieu, mieux &eacute;tudi&eacute;e et qui parait plus claire. <mark>L&apos;h&eacute;ros n&apos;est-il pas un homme divin ou un dieu terrestre?</mark> <br><font color="green">[The notion of the hero has been explained, especially in the case of the Celtic heroes, by that of the king-God, which has been studied more extensively and which seems to be clearer. Isn&apos;t the hero a divine man or a terrestrial God?]</font> <small> Stefan Czarnowski, <a name="SCSP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SCSP"><cite title="source">Le culte des h&eacute;ros et ses conditions sociale: saint Patrick, h&eacute;ros nationale de l'Irlande</cite></a> (1919) XXVI</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
